[Student "S"]
{With 11 points you would probably have bid 3\H, a limit raise, if North hadn't overcalled.

But you now doubt your \DQ is worth 2 points so you just say 2\H.

Now South comes in with 2\S and it is passed around to you. 

With a known 9-card fit this hand is worth a 3\H bid.

Everybody passes.

West would play 3\H.

Click 

East plays 3\H. South leads \DA, \DK, \DJ. North plays first the \D10, then \D2. 

<b>East plays 3\H. South leads \DA, \DK, \DJ. North plays first the \D10, then \D2.</b>

Losers: \S 2 : \H 1 : \D 3 : \C 0 : Total = 6

Although there are two \S losers in your hand, one can either be ruffed in dummy or discarded on a high \C. So you really only have one loser too many.

You should realize that if you ruff this \D with one of dummy's teensy \Hs it will be over-ruffed. North did signal a doubleton. The loss of the teensy \H doesn't worry you, you have plenty of them. But the loss of the opportunity to dump a loser should worry you a lot. 

So don't ruff at all. Discard a \S. Now you can ruff your other \S loser in dummy.

Be ever watchful for situations where you may be over-ruffed. 

Often, like in this deal, you can discard a loser instead.}
[Play "W"]DA

